40|$|The paper {{examines}} a delegated monitoring problem between {{investors and}} a bank holding {{a portfolio of}} correlated <b>balloon</b> <b>loans</b> displaying “contagion. ” Moral hazard prevents the bank from monitoring continuously unless it is compensated with the right incentive-compatible contract. Under the Monotone-Likelihood-Ratio Property (MLRP), the asset pool is liquidated when losses exceed a cut-off rule. The bank bears a relatively high share of the risk initially, {{as it should have}} high-powered incentives to monitor, but its long term financial stake tapers off as losses unfold. Securitization can approximate the optimal contract. The sponsor provides the trust with credit enhancement {{in the form of a}} weighted portfolio of collateralized debt obligations which is funded by the proceeds of the sale and extends into the cut-off rule. In compensation the trust pays servicing fees as well as rent-preserving fees if the sponsor has a high discount rate. Rather than being detrimental, well-designed securitization seems an effective and convenient means of implementing the second best...|$|R
